The serializer is not able to reason about the CurrentDepth because the JsonReader does not increment\decrement when the first token is an [object or array](https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/b506d4a4ff6ffe1a1877016811e2266eacc2ebbc/src/System.Text.Json/src/System/Text/Json/Reader/Utf8JsonReader.cs#L923).

This issue also likely applies to JsonDocument and perhaps to JsonWriter as well, which should be match any semantic changes to JsonReader.

The serializer would like to detect a bad converter that reads (or writes) too much or too little causing a difference in before and after depth. Something like this:
```cs
int beforeDepth = reader.CurrentDepth;
if (tokenType == JsonTokenType.StartObject || tokenType == JsonTokenType.StartArray)
{
    beforeDepth--;
}

Read(tokenType, ref state, ref reader); // Calls a converter.

if (reader.CurrentDepth != beforeDepth)
{
    throw new Exception("You read too much or too little");
}
```

However this code doesn’t work for cases that start with an object or array, or when calling JsonDocument that starts with an object or array.

Expect: straightforward semantics where StartObject and StartArray always does a +1 and EndObject\EndArray does a -1.

